<div id="review_1652999232" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1652999232" />
    <a title="Marielle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31677346-marielle"><img alt="Marielle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1461702322p2/31677346.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1652999232?book_show_action=true">May 30, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marielle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marielle" href="/user/show/31677346-marielle">Marielle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/30291196-mother-teresa-s-advice-for-jilted-lovers">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31677346-marielle?shelf=a-e-book">a-e-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31677346-marielle?shelf=c-contemporary">c-contemporary</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1652999232" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4853923732158406512">Quirky, original page turner about what could happen if The Secret became true. <br/><br/>This was a freebee on Amazon when I got this a while back, and it had been calling out to me from my TBR ever since. I&apos;m glad I started this. And I hope more people will too. My rating? I&apos;ve rounded up because things a well written, daring, original debut that I think deserved it. <br/><br/>While thinking about how to rate this, I&apos;m struck again with how much I depend on putting things in neat little boxes and not finding - or</span>
  <span id="freeText4853923732158406512" style="display:none">Quirky, original page turner about what could happen if The Secret became true. <br /><br />This was a freebee on Amazon when I got this a while back, and it had been calling out to me from my TBR ever since. I'm glad I started this. And I hope more people will too. My rating? I've rounded up because things a well written, daring, original debut that I think deserved it. <br /><br />While thinking about how to rate this, I'm struck again with how much I depend on putting things in neat little boxes and not finding - or knowing - of a box to put this lovely, original, quirky story in. And then I was struck by the thought that whatever I was going to write so that you, the reader of this review, would know what to expect, it probably was going to put you off, because, well, most people like to read books that fit into nice little boxes too. This author purposely went and written a blend that's never been done: religious self help mixed into a romance, suspense, mystery pack. Here here! <br /><br />I am mostly a romance reader. And romance consists of a focus on a couple with a HEA at the end, most preferably with some hot sexy scenes thrown in, but not too much, otherwise it becomes erotica. Without the sexy scenes it almost immediately becomes a 'clean' romance with the stigma it's for super religious readers only. Suspense focusses on the solving of a puzzle and YA on, well, young adults. <br /><br />This book would be a women's fiction, I guess. It's not mainly about the romance, although it does play a large part. It's not mainly on the solving of a puzzle, although yes... It has sex, but of the closed door varierty, with a single first person POV which gives it a YA-feel, but without the young adults. It is however a coming of age book in that it has a heroine striving to become her true person and finding what she does best. <br /><br />Mweh, I hear some readers of this review thinking. The great part about this book however is that it does all of the above, but in a way that's truly fresh. I mean, look at the title alone. And it's not a holy book, but in fact the title is the name of a business the heroine started and made a lot of money with. It's also a book about opposites, bad and good and grey. <br /><br />So, when you're in a slumb or when you like to try something new on a more regular basis, try this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4853923732158406512" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


