<span id="freeTextContainer6822148232045569299">This book definitely crosses several genres but that is one of the things I liked best about it. Some parts made me laugh, some parts kept me guessing, some parts had me wishing I had a guy like Glen or a friend like Tara, and some parts had me not able to put it down. <br/>Personally I could relate to Tara&apos;s inner struggle with the religion she was brought up in versus the way she sees the world as an adult. Even though she considers herself a not very devoted atheist, she still feels a pull to the </span>
  <span id="freeText6822148232045569299" style="display:none">This book definitely crosses several genres but that is one of the things I liked best about it. Some parts made me laugh, some parts kept me guessing, some parts had me wishing I had a guy like Glen or a friend like Tara, and some parts had me not able to put it down. <br />Personally I could relate to Tara's inner struggle with the religion she was brought up in versus the way she sees the world as an adult. Even though she considers herself a not very devoted atheist, she still feels a pull to the church she grew up in.<br />I have to say I didn't much care for Betsy from the beginning though. I liked that she was so outspoken as a child, but from the start she seemed to be too overbearing on Tara. Sure she was there with her survival/recovery kit whenever Tara was blue, but she seemed to take joy in Tara's pain in a way. I don't appreciate or trust friends or family who think they know what is best for you better than you know for yourself. Betsy was just way to controlling from the start.<br />I loved that Tara named her Amethyst Bob, spoke to it, and referred to it as a him. Let's just say I know a think or two about naming important inanimate objects, although mine are not named after spirit guides.<br />Without spoiling anything for anyone who hasn't read this book yet I love the way it ends with the tiniest hint that we haven't seen the last of these gals.<br />I appreciated the humor mixed with the darker stuff The book took a more mysterious turn than I was expecting and that was the point where i couldn't' put the book down until I found out how it was all going to turn out.<br />I will definitely be checking out the site mentioned in the afterword as well. And if there is a sequel, I will definitely be checking that out too!<br /></span>
